<HH> ============= Screen: Revised pathway ====================== </HH>

<Vertical id="fba2_revised_pathway">
<Markdown>
## Revised Competing Behavior Pathway

Here is JJ's original pathway for reference. Now that you've identified escape-focused strategies, revise the plan by filling in the three boxes below.
</Markdown>

<Collapsible id="fba2_original_pathway_ref" title="JJ's Original Pathway (click to expand)">
<Mermaid id="fba2_pathway_ref_diagram"><![CDATA[
flowchart LR
  A["Antecedent:<br/>Roommate tells Johnny<br/>to go to bed"] --> PB["Problem Behavior:<br/>Johnny runs out of<br/>the room laughing"] --> C["Consequence:<br/>Roommate runs after<br/>him, nagging"]
  C --> F["Function:<br/>Escape"]
  A --> DB["Desired Behavior:<br/>Johnny goes to bed<br/>appropriately"] --> DO["Desired Outcome:<br/>Johnny goes to sleep"]
  class A ant
  class PB beh
  class C con
  class F func
  class DB desired
  class DO outcome
  classDef ant fill:#fff3cd,stroke:#ffc107,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
  classDef beh fill:#cfe2ff,stroke:#0d6efd,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
  classDef con fill:#d1e7dd,stroke:#198754,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
  classDef func fill:#f8d7da,stroke:#dc3545,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
  classDef desired fill:#d0e8ff,stroke:#0a58ca,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
  classDef outcome fill:#c3e6cb,stroke:#28a745,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
]]></Mermaid>
</Collapsible>

<Markdown>
### Your Revised Plan

Using the escape-focused antecedent and consequence strategies you identified, fill in the revised pathway:
</Markdown>

<Markdown>**Antecedent + new strategies** (what happens before bedtime, and what strategies will you add to prevent escape?):</Markdown>
<TextArea id="fba2_revised_antecedent" rows="3" placeholder="Roommate tells Johnny to go to bed + your chosen antecedent strategies..." />

<Markdown>**Desired behavior** (what do you want Johnny to do instead of running away?):</Markdown>
<TextArea id="fba2_revised_desired" rows="2" placeholder="What should Johnny do at bedtime?" />

<Markdown>**Consequence/Outcome + new strategies** (what happens after the desired behavior, and what consequence strategies support it?):</Markdown>
<TextArea id="fba2_revised_consequence" rows="3" placeholder="Johnny goes to sleep + your chosen consequence strategies..." />
</Vertical>


<HH> ============= Screen: Plan selection ======================= </HH>

<Vertical id="fba2_plan_selection">
<Markdown>
## Behavior Modification Plan

Annie has two plans to present. Both include data collection over a 2-week period.

**Plan A: Escape-Focused Plan**

- _Antecedent strategies:_ Create a predictable bedtime routine with a visual schedule; use a timer to signal each step; give 10- and 5-minute warnings before bedtime.
- _Consequence strategies:_ Provide positive reinforcement (sticker chart) when Johnny goes to bed on time; ignore escape behaviors (don't chase); use a "bedtime pass" for one approved brief delay per night.

**Plan B: Sensory-Focused Plan**

- _Antecedent strategies:_ Play calming music in the bedroom; use a weighted blanket; dim lights gradually; provide a lavender-scented pillow.
- _Consequence strategies:_ Allow access to a sensory toy (fidget) in bed; redirect sensory-seeking behavior to appropriate sensory input; track which sensory inputs are most effective.
</Markdown>

<MarkupProblem id="fba2_plan_choice" title="Choose the Best Plan"><![CDATA[
>>Which plan do you think will work best for Johnny?<<

(x) Plan A — Escape-Focused Plan
( ) Plan B — Sensory-Focused Plan

[explanation]
**Plan A** is correct. Since the function of Johnny's behavior is **escape**, the intervention plan must address escape. Plan A uses antecedent strategies to make bedtime less aversive (predictable routine, warnings, timers) and consequence strategies that don't reinforce escape behavior (ignoring running away, not chasing). Plan B targets sensory needs, which is not the function of Johnny's behavior.
[/explanation]
]]></MarkupProblem>
</Vertical>


<HH> ============= Screen: Escape plan display ================== </HH>

<Vertical id="fba2_escape_plan_display">
<Markdown>
## The Escape-Focused Behavior Modification Plan

| | |
|---|---|
| **Target Behavior** | Johnny does not go to bed on time |
| **Function of Behavior** | Escape |
| **Behavior Goal** | Johnny will go to bed on time when told, without running away, for 4 out of 5 bedtimes over a 2-week period |

**Antecedent Strategies:**
- Create a predictable bedtime routine with a visual schedule showing each step
- Use a timer to clearly signal when each routine step begins and ends
- Give 10-minute and 5-minute advance warnings before bedtime begins
- Incorporate a brief preferred activity (e.g., short story) as part of the routine to make bedtime less aversive
- Allow limited choices within the routine (e.g., "Do you want to brush teeth or put on pajamas first?")

**~~Replacement Behaviors (Teach):~~** ~~Not applicable for this plan — replacement behaviors are used when the function involves skill deficits rather than escape from aversive conditions.~~

**Consequence Strategies:**
- Provide positive reinforcement (sticker chart, verbal praise) when Johnny goes to bed on time
- Ignore escape behaviors — do not chase or engage when he runs away
- Do not provide attention or reinforcement during escape behavior
- Use a "bedtime pass" — Johnny is allowed one brief, approved delay (e.g., one more minute, one more sip of water) per night
- If Johnny gets in bed and stays, provide brief positive attention and praise

**Data Collection:**
- Track whether Johnny goes to bed on time each night for 2 weeks
- Note any modifications or deviations from the plan
</Markdown>

<Markdown>**In the box below, type the parts of this plan that you like:**</Markdown>
<TextArea id="fba2_plan_likes" rows="3" placeholder="What parts of this plan do you think will be most effective?" />
</Vertical>


<HH> ============= Screen: Sensory plan check =================== </HH>

<Vertical id="fba2_sensory_plan_check">
<Markdown>
## Check for Understanding: The Sensory-Focused Plan

Here is Plan B in detail:

| | |
|---|---|
| **Target Behavior** | Johnny does not go to bed on time |
| **Function of Behavior** | Sensory |
| **Behavior Goal** | Johnny will go to bed on time when told, without running away, for 4 out of 5 bedtimes over a 2-week period |

**Antecedent Strategies:**
- Play calming music in the bedroom 15 minutes before bedtime
- Use a weighted blanket on Johnny's bed
- Dim the lights gradually during the bedtime routine
- Provide a lavender-scented pillow
- Allow Johnny to hold a preferred textured object during the routine

**~~Replacement Behaviors (Teach):~~** ~~Not applicable for this plan.~~

**Consequence Strategies:**
- Allow access to a sensory toy (fidget spinner, stress ball) while in bed
- Redirect sensory-seeking behavior to appropriate sensory input
- Track which sensory inputs are most effective

**Reinforcement Plan:**
- Provide praise when Johnny uses sensory tools appropriately
- Allow extra time with preferred sensory items as a reward
- Track sensory triggers and adjust environment accordingly

**Data Collection:**
- Track whether Johnny goes to bed on time each night for 2 weeks
- Note which sensory accommodations were used each night
</Markdown>

<MarkupProblem id="fba2_sensory_check_choice" title="Why Not the Sensory Plan?"><![CDATA[
>>Why wouldn't this be a good plan for Johnny?<<

( ) It does not address the function of behavior (attention)
(x) It does not address the function of behavior (escape)
( ) It does not include positive reinforcement
( ) It does not include positive punishment

[explanation]
This plan addresses **sensory** needs, but Johnny's behavior function is **escape**. The plan does not address why Johnny is running away — to avoid going to bed. A good intervention must match the function of the behavior. Since Johnny's behavior is maintained by escape, the plan needs strategies that make bedtime less aversive and don't reinforce escape.
[/explanation]
]]></MarkupProblem>
</Vertical>


